column80: I use mushrooms to ease my depression. It doesn't get rid of it. I dose every 2-4 months. It helps me break out of the internal self hate thoughts and feelings of worthlessness. It doesn't stop the thoughts, but helps me recognize when they are happening and that they are unfounded. It changes my perspective for a time. Instead of seeing myself through a microscope and dissecting every awkward encounter or bad decision I'm able to take a step back and realize the sky isn't falling because I said good morning to someone at 2 in the afternoon. I'm not an idiot loser, I just misspoke while I was distracted thinking about work.

column80: The framing of your questions might be a little off in my case. You're looking for immediate, let's call them "medical" benefits for our purposes. In large part tryptamine psychedelics changed me over-all and for the better. Changes in the context of cognitive flexibility (I.e. permanent agnosticism [see Robert Anton Wilson] ) and spiritually in terms of seeing things as connected gradients not binaries in nature is now tattooed on me. See Terence McKenna's commentsry on "being a psychedelic person" . Anecdotal as it may be, it gives a good overall sense of ehat many of us experiened over the years. Now habitual thought patterns of the day to day prosaic realities sure that's a bit different. Breaking habits like cigarettes for example. Those things last for a bit and old patterns do return. As a result psilocybin is absolutely helpful in kickstarting the breaking of patterns. This must be followed by real work but getting a head start is a great thing too.

column80: As a writer and poet, I often experience creative breakthroughs (such as finding useful connections between two topics I might be interested in) while tripping which can lead to days or weeks of reflection and productivity. Outside of creativity, I find that I am frequently more patient with myself, more forgiving of my own shortcomings, and more eager to find new routines going forward. As someone prone to psychosis, too much repeated use of moderate dose psilocybin in a short period can lead to increased paranoia, anxiety, and thought spirals, but this has never been the case with occasional use.

Exploring those negative events led me to seek therapeutic guidance which, in turn, led me to Internal Family Systems Therapy. IFS has allowed me to better understand my emotional reactions and has given me a framework for an ongoing self-led healing path.  More than 1 year following my "trip", I continue to have experiences in nature and connecting with other humans that bring child-like joy. When have negative experiences, I look at these as opportunities to grow and understand myself better. My "hero dose" set in motion a series of psychological shifts, healing work and exploring new interests that have endured over a significant period of time.

I began using mushrooms a lot at high doses in 2023. I had several 'bad trips' which equated to negative experiences while high on the mushroom. These experiences turned very severe so that by the end of the year, I had such horrendous schizophrenic psychosis induced by the mushroom, and before that paranoid psychosis, that my relationship with the mushroom has forever been changed. I am hesitant to take them again, the schizophrenic time loops are really awful and I hate being in psychosis.  I began experimenting with ketamine as well in 2023, and I now see it as a much more potentially beneficial psychedelic than mushrooms. I believe mushrooms is neither good or evil, but it does not give the grandiose knowledge people are claiming it to, it is something far more sinister to mankind. Sinister because it is natural, and we have to remember that all of Life is a competition amongst all the members of Life, including the mushroom.  So let's be real and accept the fact that all psychedelics may induce schizophrenia during the trip, and may affect those who consume it for the rest of their life, because the visions and thoughts may turn into beliefs about the nature of reality. Am I lucky or blessed to have seen past life and imagine that I witnessed the feeding of quantum worlds, Hindu deities, and demons? or cursed? Magical thinking, schizophrenic hallucinations, catatonia... these are all possible outcomes for days or even months or years afterwards... But you have to be strong and believe in your own mind and in the end, I always feel much better off, and grateful for the visions that aren't too painful to witness.  Must be noted that I have ingested psychedelics for a long time (20 years) and that one large dose doesn't just ruin a person. And I am not mentally impaired from these experiences... I do not suffer, and it has not affected my life negatively, only positively, but one must be willing to accept that your worldview might be changed by inducing these substances at great doses.

column80: I don’t actually like magic mushrooms. They make me wildly introspective. This last year I’ve warmed up a bit to them but I think I’m going to stop again. I have adhd and autism. I didn’t get the science and math autism, I got the substance abuse autism.   I’ve always wanted my brain to shutoff. I’m introspective and aware of myself and everything around me on an outrageous level. I don’t want to “feel” myself out more.   Magic mushrooms piss me off the first week because I’m emotionally disregulated for a week. Then it takes another week or so to feel like myself again. I’ve never used them medicinally so I don’t know what microdosing feels like.   Either way,  it’s a personal experience. It terms of what I want out of a drug. Mushrooms are a pass for me. I’d need to have something pretty specific I’m going after and even then, mushrooms wouldn’t be my first choice.   However, if you e never done drugs and are struggling or need a pick me up, I know these are life changing for people.

I would say that the major effect I've noticed is an increased flexibility in my thinking and ability to take in and synthesize new ideas. It helps me form connections and see patterns in information which has greatly increased my capacity to understand new knowledge. I have found this to be a permanent effect, although it does seem to peak in the weeks/months immediately following use. I find that during that period, I am very drawn to reading books and seeking out other sources of knowledge, and that I have very vivid clarity of understanding.   I would also note that it has hugely affected the way I listen to music and consume other forms of art, and that I have a much deeper appreciation of these things that has stuck well after using psilocybin. Although these feelings peak during a trip, I feel that my appreciation for music especially has been forever changed.   Other lingering effects include an increased sense of well-being, connection to others, and the breaking down of negative thought patterns and habits, however I find these effects short-lived compared to the others, and have often found myself slipping back into old habits in the weeks & months following use. They have also made me much more open to new experiences and changes in my life, although I find that this effect also diminishes over time as I find myself slipping into old comforts.

column105: A friend in the mental health research/alternative health field suggested I try this therapy. I proceeded to apply for a section 57 and once I obtained it, and after a preparation process that took one year that included abstinence from drugs and alcohol and anti depressant medication, I went to a private home and did it with a private guardian/therapist. The many professional mental workers who were offering the therapy wanted $2000 but the private guardian did it for free. I felt a slight sense of gimmick or snake oil salesmanship from the psychologists who were connected to the project. The private guardian seemed more genuine and authentic. My goals were to explore and repair my emotional landscape. To reduce depression and fear of death. To gain understanding of my path and find a way to cherish my life,  I had to appeal a few times to receive my section 57.
column108: My symptoms were sadness, sense of worthlessness and meaninglessness. What I liked about the session was that the place was comfortable and reassuring. The private guardian was a person I trusted and who knew me. That person had been on a long personal quest. I could relate to them. The place had cool paintings and textiles and an atmosphere that was spiritual to me. I felt cared for by family. Maybe linked to my personal mental challenges that I was appreciative of that aspect. The music was an essential part of the process, following the bright and dark places it was carrying me to. The very intriguing part of my experience during that session was that I had a question and answer with the ´plant’. I was able to see some irony and playfulness with the spirit of the medicine. There was a feeling of partnership. At times it felt like a trickster, it’s hard to explain. I felt I became the plant and was a seed underground. I was visited by strong male and female representations of support in my life, I connected with maternal lineage. I saw my mother who is deceased in a mountain and my grandmother as the snow. I spend a lot of time in the mountains and this made the connection of a notion of home and love in the external world to me. I could go on, The experience was profound yet incomplete, I have changed since starting the whole preparation and session. And post session integration.

column80: ego dissolution is a violation of everything i thought I knew. It is like becoming a strongly sentient child, and having to relearn certain concepts that you built entirely on egotistical referendums. You wont know how inflated your ego is until your changing your minds tire, many things you assess and learn about include your own opinion. For example, I no longer judge a person by their look, race, mental capacity etc. but rather by their direct actions and decision thought process. A bad choice with confident irrationality can be the difference in "fate" and "fumbled", is imperative to know negative energy and avoid it. If I can see truly good improvements in the world as if a collective conscience has ascended a level. In conclusion, psilocybin will target your bad habits and disrespect your feelings like an army sergeant, but like ex. antidepressants you have a period of adjustment foreshadowing whether you can take them, or you are suddenly afraid of them.

column80: I always get an enhanced feeling of inner peace and conection with the universe as it is which lead me to the spiritual feeling of flow and love for my reality and a deeper freedom to be myself and act out of my authentical motivations instead of the motivations learned from the society and the system.

I am using various kinds that have way different effects. 3 main categories they fit into 1) Heightened spirituality ( Best sitting around a campfire in the woods ) 2) 70s tripping. laughing, hallucinations and a feeling that everything is great in your world. 3) body stone, heightened libido ( don't do this type alone )

I don’t find the effects to automatically have a lasting impact on my perspective, but if I pause to remember/reflect on what I learned or realized during the experience, a change of perspective or outlook is apparent and can be applied to daily life.  If that makes sense!
